# Authentication Patterns - MUST FOLLOW

## Authentication Architecture

This project uses **Server Actions + JWT + HTTP-only Cookies** for authentication.
The frontend acts as a BFF (Backend-for-Frontend) — all API calls are proxied
through `/api/[...path]` route handlers; tokens never touch client JavaScript.

**CRITICAL**: Tokens NEVER touch client JavaScript. All auth logic runs server-side.

---

## Backend URL in Server-Side Code (H3)

### ✅ CORRECT: Use getBackendUrl()

```typescript
// src/app/api/lib/getBackendUrl.ts  — server-only helper
import "server-only";

export function getBackendUrl(): string {
  const url = process.env.API_URL;
  if (!url) {
    if (process.env.NODE_ENV === "production") {
      throw new Error("API_URL env var is required in production");
    }
    return "http://localhost:3002";
  }
  return url;
}
```

```typescript
// Server Action or API route handler
import { getBackendUrl } from "@/app/api/lib/getBackendUrl";

const BACKEND_URL = getBackendUrl(); // uses API_URL, not NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL
```

### ❌ WRONG: Using NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL in server code

```typescript
// NEVER DO THIS in Server Actions or API route handlers
const url = process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL; // ❌ leaks backend origin to browser
```

**Rule:** `NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL` may appear only in client-only utilities (browser
widgets that must know an endpoint directly). All server-side calls must use
`getBackendUrl()` → `API_URL`.

